    Data validation with pointblank

    valid-with-pointblank.Rmd
    library(convo)
library(pointblank)

    Read in controlled vocabulary specification

    - level: 1
  desc: The type layer
  req: Y
  stubs:
    - stub: ID
      desc: Unique identifier
      valid:
        - col_exists()
        - col_vals_not_null()
        - col_is_numeric()
        - col_vals_between(1000, 99999)
    - stub: IND
      desc: Binary indicator
      valid:
        - col_is_numeric()
        - col_vals_in_set(c(0,1))
    - stub: AMT
      desc: Non-negative, summable quantity
      valid:
        - col_is_numeric()
        - col_vals_gte(0)
    - stub: VAL
      desc: Value
      valid:
        - col_is_numeric()
    - stub: CAT
      desc: Category
      valid:
        - col_is_character()
    - stub: CD
      desc: System-generated code
      valid:
        - col_is_character()
    - stub: DT
      desc: Calendar date in YYYY-MM-DD format
      valid:
        - col_is_date()
- level: 2
  req: Y
  desc: The entity layer
  stubs:
  - stub: DRIVER
    desc: Ridershare driver
  - stub: RIDER
    desc: Ridershare passenger
  - stub: TRIP
    desc: Complete trip (request to arrival)
  - stub: ORIG
    desc: Initial position
  - stub: DEST
    desc: Final position
  - stub: COST
    desc: Financial burden
- level: 3
  req: N
  stubs:
  - stub: CITY
    desc: City name
  - stub: ZIP
    desc: Five digit zip code
  - stub: LAT
    desc: Latitude
  - stub: LON
    desc: Longitude
  - stub: DIST
    desc: Distance in miles
  - stub: TIME
    desc: Time in minutes
  - stub: RATE
    desc: Rating on five star scale

    Under each dictionary entry, the valid: key allows us to specify any relevant checks using pointblank syntax.

    convo_file <- system.file("", "vocab-test-2.yml", package = "convo")
convo <- read_convo(convo_file)
print(convo)
    #> Level 1
#> - 
#>  Level 2
#> - 
#>  Level 3
#> -

    Write controlled vocabulary to a pointblank config file

    df <-
data.frame(
  c_1 = as.Date("2020-01-01"),
  c_2 = "a",
  d_1 = 3,
  d_2 = 0.5,
  d_3 = TRUE
)
    write_pb(convo,
              col_names = names(df),
              filename = "vocab-valid.yml",
              path = tempdir())
    read_fn: ~structure(list(c_1 = 1, c_2 = 1, d_1 = 1, d_2 = 1, d_3 = 1), class = "data.frame",
  row.names = c(NA, -1))
tbl_name: .na.character
label: '[2020-11-09|07:58:43]'
locale: en
steps:
- col_is_date:
    columns: vars(c_1)
- col_is_date:
    columns: vars(c_2)
- col_is_numeric:
    columns: vars(d_1)
- col_is_numeric:
    columns: vars(d_2)
- col_is_numeric:
    columns: vars(d_3)
- col_vals_between:
    columns: vars(d_1)
    left: 1.0
    right: 2.0
    inclusive:
    - true
    - true
- col_vals_between:
    columns: vars(d_2)
    left: 1.0
    right: 2.0
    inclusive:
    - true
    - true
- col_vals_between:
    columns: vars(d_3)
    left: 1.0
    right: 2.0
    inclusive:
    - true
    - true

    Use pointblank config file for validation

    Using pointblank, we can read back in our validation agent from this YAML file.

    agent <- pointblank::yaml_read_agent(file.path(tempdir(), "vocab-valid.yml"))

    This object can then directly be used in validation. For example:

    agent %>%
  remove_read_fn() %>%
  set_tbl(df) %>%
  interrogate()

    Creating object directly

    Alternatively, you can make a pointblank agent object directly with convo::create_pb_agent().

    agent <- create_pb_agent(convo, df)
interrogate(agent)
